<Layout title="Advisory">
  <h1>Advisory</h1>

  <p>
    The threat landscape is moving faster than most institutions can track.
    AI is speeding up how quickly existing tactics get deployed at scale,
    and it's producing genuinely new ones — such as LLM-grooming.
    I work at that frontier,
    tracking how tactics evolve, and
    helping institutions identify threats and effective countermeasures.
  </p>

  <p>
    That means looking outward as much as inward. When preparing for an
    election, for example, the more useful question usually isn't what
    happened here five years ago — it's what happened somewhere else last
    week.
  </p>

  <p>
    For now, this work is focused on organizations — governments,
    parliaments, and related public bodies.
  </p>

  <h2>Engagement types</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Threat and vulnerability assessment</strong> — evaluating where
      an institution's information environment or AI systems are exposed to
      manipulation, misuse, or failure, benchmarked against the current
      frontier rather than historical incidents.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>FIMI analysis</strong> — assessing foreign information
      manipulation and interference campaigns: detection methodology,
      evidence review, and characterization of tactics, drawing on patterns
      observed globally, not just locally.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Who it's for</h2>
  <p>
    Governments, parliaments, and public institutions who need an
    independent researcher's assessment rather than a vendor's pitch.
  </p>

  <h2>Contact</h2>
  <p>
    The best starting point is a short email describing the problem:{' '}
    <a href="mailto:tim.niven.public@gmail.com">tim.niven.public@gmail.com</a>.
  </p>
</Layout>
